OOPS OOPS is a utility that provides a convenient method of correcting amistyped command without retyping the entire command.  The command thatis to be corrected must still be on the screen for OOPS to be used.OOPS can be also used to change the filenames or options of previouscommands.  This is useful when performing repeated operations ondifferent files and/or different parameters.To use OOPS, simply type:	OOPS <ENTER>If OOPS is installed as the Immediate Execution Program (IEP), thenuse the command:	* <ENTER>Using the UP-ARROW or DOWN-ARROW keys, move the cursor to the line thatyou want to edit.  When the cursor is over the desired line, press <ENTER>,<F3> or <.>.  (<ENTER> clears the screen below the line to be edited,and <F3> or <.> do not.)Once a line has been selected, it may be edited by using the same functionsthat are available in the BASIC EDIT command.  These are described in detailwith examples in the TRSDOS 6 Disk System Owners Manual.  This manual shouldhave come with your system, but can be ordered from Radio Shack, #26-0316.A summary of each command is provided below as a quick reference.<ENTER>		Submits the command to the operating system command		interpreter.<BREAK>		Exits OOPS without performing any operation.  If OOPS		is in a special mode, the first <BREAK> exits the		special mode and a second <BREAK> exits OOPS.  You can tell		if you are in a special mode by looking at the bottom-		right part of the screen.  For example, if you see the word		'Change', you are currently in the 'change' mode.<I>		Enter insertion mode.  Characters will be inserted in		front of the character under the cursor.		Pressing <ENTER> submits the command to the system.		Pressing <F3>, <BREAK>, <SHIFT><UPARROW> or any other		control character exits insert mode.<X>		Enters insertion mode, but positions the cursor at the		end of the line.  See the <I> command for more information.<H> or <T>	Deletes all characters to the right of the cursor,		and enters insert mode.  See the <I> command.<S>		Searches for the next character that is entered and		moves the cursor to that position.  If the character		that is specified is not found to the right of the cursor,		the cursor is moved to the end of the line.  		The search is case-sensitive; in other words, if you		search for the letter t, the uppercase letter T		will not be found by the search.			Page  1<C>		Changes the character under the cursor to the next character		that is typed.  The cursor moves one position to the right.<D>		Deletes the character under the cursor and moves the text on		the right of the cursor to the left to fill the hole.<K>		Searches for the next character that is typed and deletes		the characters between the current position and the		search-character.  If the character is not found, no		characters are deleted.		If the character to search for is <ENTER>, the		characters to the right of the cursor are deleted.		As with the Search command, the search is case-sensitive.<0> thru <9>	The numeric keys allow you to specify a repetition count.		For example, pressing <5><S><X> causes OOPS to move the cursor		to the 5th occurrence of the letter x.  A repeat value from		2 to 79 can be entered.  As the digits are entered, they will		appear in the status area at the bottom of the screen.		The following commands can be repeated:			<S>		Search Mode			<K>		Kill (Delete String) Mode			<D>		Delete Mode			<C>		Change Mode			<SPACE>		Move Cursor Right			<RIGHT-ARROW>	Move Cursor Right			<LEFT-ARROW>	Move Cursor Left		In the case of the change command (<C>), the count remaining		in the repeat is displayed at the bottom of the screen		as the changes are made.		Commands not listed above reset the repeat count to zero		if one was specified.		If the repeat rate causes the command to be performed		an invalid number of times, the command is performed		until the end of the line is reached, then the remaining		repeat count is discarded.  For example, attempting to		delete 90 characters will only delete the number of		characters on the line.<.>		Allows one or both digits of the repeat value to be erased.		This can be done until an edit command is entered.		The last digit (ones' digit) is the first removed.<U>		Aborts all changes made so far and restores the line to its		original state.  The cursor is positioned to column 1.<F1> or <L>	Moves the cursor to the column 1.  <F2>		Moves the cursor one column past the last character on the		line.<LEFT-ARROW>	Moves the cursor one position to the left.<RIGHT-ARROW>	Moves the cursor one position to the right.<F3>		Exits any special mode OOPS may be in.  These are		displayed at the bottom-right of the screen.  If OOPS is not		in a special mode when <F3> is pressed, it is ignored.				Page  2Technical InformationOOPS runs in the library overlay area and does not disturb memorybelow 0x2600 or above 0x2FFF.  Programs may invoke OOPS, but OOPS will not return control to them.The display state is not altered by OOPS;  therefore, if the cursor isoff when OOPS is executed, it will not be very usable.  Reverse videotext cannot be edited reliably, and may not be recognized by the command.interpreter.The Model 4/4P/4D version of OOPS must be used with LS-DOS 6.2.0 or later.To install OOPS as the Immediate Execution Program (IEP), use the command:	COPY OOPS/CMD SYS13/SYS:0 (C=N)Once done, OOPS can be invoked by typing:	* <ENTER>OOPS utilizes the @VDCTL SVC to read old commands from the screen, thusallowing it to edit commands other than the last command entered.  Thecommand must still be on the screen for OOPS to be able to access it.The edited command is supplied to the operating system via the@CMNDI SVC.803011